title: Proton and Deuteron Double Differential Cross Sections At Angles from 10 Degree to 60 Degree from be, C, Al, Fe, Cu, Ge, W and Pb Under 558-MeV Proton Irradiation.

x4freetext: Proton and Deuteron Double Differential Cross Sections
At  Angles  from 10 Degree to 60 Degree from be, C, Al,
Fe, Cu, Ge, W and Pb Under 558-MeV Proton  Irradiation.

x4codes.hlp: Langley Research Center, NASA Langley Station, VA, United States of America

flag.hlp: Reference to related data compiled in another entry

x4freetext: The Largest Correction to the Data Involved a
Calculation of the Multiple Scattering. The Data were
Also Corrected For Energy Loss Through the
Spectrometer.  Both Corrections were Obtained Through
All Targets were Commercially Available and were of
Natural Isotopic Abundance.The Targets were Approx.
10-cm Square or Larger with the Exception of the
Beryllium and Germanium Targets Which were 5.08-cm
System. The System Measured Both the Time of Flight of
Secondary Charged Particles Over a 488-cm Flight Path
And the Energy Deposited in a Plastic Scintillator,
12.7 cm in Diameter and 30.48 cm Long.
Proton Beam Energy Measurements. 488-cm Flight Path.

x4codes.hlp: Space Radiation Effects Lab., Newport News, VA, United States of America

x4freetext: The Uncertainty in the Cross Section Values
Varies with Particle Energy from +-9.3% at 50-MeV to
+-11.4% at 558-MeV For Protons and from +-8% at  90-MeV
To 8.3% at 350-MeV For Deuterons.  Noany Analysis is
